    <section class="strategy-section">
      <h2>Investment Strategies for the Current Market</h2>
      <p>Identifying the <strong>best stocks to buy now</strong> is only the first step; constructing a resilient portfolio requires a thoughtful strategy tailored to your specific financial goals and risk tolerance.</p>

      <h3>The Case for Growth</h3>
      <p>When searching for the <strong>best growth stocks to buy now</strong>, investors typically focus on companies experiencing rapid expansion in revenues and earnings. These are often found in the technology, consumer discretionary, and healthcare sectors. The appeal of growth stocks lies in their potential for significant capital appreciation. However, they often trade at high valuation multiples, making them more susceptible to sharp pullbacks if growth slows or interest rates rise unexpectedly. Identifying the <strong>best growth stocks to buy now 2025</strong> requires a keen eye for businesses with sustainable, secular tailwinds—such as cloud computing, artificial intelligence, and e-commerce—rather than short-term fads.</p>

      <h3>The Value Proposition</h3>
      <p>Conversely, value investing involves seeking out companies that appear to be trading for less than their intrinsic or book value. These are often mature businesses in stable industries, such as financials, utilities, or consumer staples. While they may not offer the explosive upside of growth stocks, they frequently provide reliable dividend income and can act as a stabilizing force during market turbulence. For investors focused on capital preservation and income, high-quality value stocks are essential components of a diversified portfolio.</p>

      <h3>Looking Ahead to 2026</h3>
      <p>As we extend our time horizon and consider the <strong>best stocks to buy now 2026</strong>, the focus shifts toward durability and compounding. Businesses that can consistently generate high returns on invested capital (ROIC) and reinvest those earnings at attractive rates are the true long-term winners. These companies often possess strong economic moats—such as powerful brand recognition, network effects, or high switching costs—that protect them from competition and allow them to maintain pricing power over time.</p>
    </section>

